In mathematics, a '''Néron differential''', named after [[André Néron]], is an almost canonical choice of [[One-form|1-form]] on an [[elliptic curve]] or [[abelian variety]] defined over a [[local field]] or [[global field]]. The Néron differential behaves well on the [[Néron minimal model]]s.

For an elliptic curve of the form
:<math> y^2+a_1xy+a_3=x^3+a_2x^2+a_4x+a_6</math>
the Néron differential is
:<math>\frac{dx}{2y+a_1x+a_3}</math>

