In mathematical [[representation theory]], a '''good filtration''' is a [[Filtration (mathematics)|filtration]] of a representation of a [[reductive algebraic group]] ''G''  such that the [[subquotient]]s are isomorphic to the spaces of [[Section (fiber bundle)|sections]] ''F''(λ) of [[line bundle]]s λ over ''G''/''B'' for a [[Borel subgroup]] ''B''. In [[Characteristic (algebra)|characteristic]] 0 this is automatically true as the [[Simple module|irreducible modules]] are all of the form ''F''(λ), but this is not usually true in positive characteristic. {{harvtxt|Mathieu|1990}} showed that the [[tensor product of representations|tensor product of two modules]] ''F''(λ)⊗''F''(μ) has a good filtration, completing the results of {{harvtxt|Donkin|1985}} who proved it in most cases and {{harvtxt|Wang|1982}} who proved it in large characteristic.  {{harvtxt|Littelmann|1992}} showed that the existence of good filtrations for these tensor products also follows from [[standard monomial theory]].

