In the theory of [[algebraic groups]], a '''special group''' is a [[linear algebraic group]] ''G'' with the property that every [[principal bundle|principal ''G''-bundle]] is locally trivial in the [[Zariski topology]].  Special groups include the [[general linear group]], the [[special linear group]], and the [[symplectic group]].  Special groups are necessarily [[Connected space|connected]].  Products of special groups are special. The [[projective linear group]] is not special because there exist [[Azumaya algebras]], which are trivial over a finite [[separable extension]], but not over the base field.

[[Category:Linear algebraic groups]]


{{algebra-stub}}

In [[algebraic group]] theory, a '''thin group''' is a discrete [[Zariski topology|Zariski-dense]] subgroup of ''G''('''R''') that has infinite covolume, where ''G'' is a [[semisimple algebraic group]] over the [[real number|reals]]. This is in contrast to a [[lattice (group)|lattice]], which is a discrete subgroup of finite covolume.

The theory of "group expansion" ([[expander graph]] properties of related [[Cayley graph]]s) for particular thin groups has been applied to arithmetic properties of [[Apollonian circles]] and in [[Zaremba's conjecture]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gauss.math.yale.edu/~ho2/MSRI_Bourgain.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-07-24 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729070337/http://gauss.math.yale.edu/~ho2/MSRI_Bourgain.pdf |archivedate=2014-07-29 |df= }}</ref>

